It is true that its author has sometimes allowed inconsisteucies to romain, as, for instance, when in one passage, at the beginning of his notes on the Aeneid, he quotes arma uirumque cano as the first words of the Aeneid, and two lines below says that Virgil began differently. Again, the author sometimes refers to a note which he either never wrote, or which has disappeared from our manuscripts. This case, however, is quite exceptional. The commentary constantly refers back to notes which really exist, an almost decisivo mark of its coming from one hand.

It is plain, 1 think, that the commentary of Servius is the work of an adherent of theold religion.
